			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">IN ORDER THAT THERE MAY BE PROPER REPRESENTATION AT THE MEETING, YOU ARE URGED TO SIGN, DATE AND RETURN THE ENCLOSED PROXY IN THE POSTAGE-PAID ENVELOPE PROVIDED, OR TO VOTE ELECTRONICALLY AS PROVIDED IN THE INSTRUCTIONS INCLUDED HEREWITH.</font>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">THE FIRST OF LONG ISLAND CORPORATION</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">10 Glen Head Road</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Glen Head, New York 11545</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">(516) 671-4900</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">PROXY STATEMENT</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">INFORMATION ABO</font><a name="InfoAboutAnnualMeetStockholders"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">UT THE ANNUAL MEETING OF STOCKHOLDERS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The</font><font style="display: inline;"> accompanying proxy is being solicited by the Board of Directors (&#x201C;Board&#x201D;) of The First of Long Island Corporation (&#x201C;Corporation&#x201D; or &#x201C;Company&#x201D;) for use at the Annual Meeting of Stockholders to be held at 3:30 P.M. local time at The Carltun, Eisenhower Park, 1899 Hempstead Turnpike, East Meadow, New York on April 17, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;The approximate date on which proxy statements and forms of proxy are first being sent or given to stockholders is March 16, 2018.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Proxies </font><font style="display: inline;">in</font><font style="display: inline;"> the accompanying form that are properly executed and duly returned to the Corporation, or voted electronically, will be voted at the meeting </font><font style="display: inline;">in accordance with the instructions provided.&nbsp;&nbsp;Where no instructions are indicated, </font><font style="display: inline;">properly</font><font style="display: inline;"> executed proxies will be voted &#x201C;For&#x201D; the proposals set forth in this proxy statement.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">Each proxy granted may be revoked at any time prior to its exercise by written notice filed with the secretary of the Corporation, by the submission of a later dated and executed proxy or by notice given during the meeting by the stockholder to the presiding officer of the meeting.&nbsp;&nbsp;The presence in person or by proxy of the holders of a majority of the shares entitled to vote at the annual meeting constitutes a quorum for the transaction of business.&nbsp;&nbsp;The meeting (whether or not a quorum is present) may be adjourned to a subsequent date, provided notice of the time and place to which the meeting is adjourned are announced at the meeting at which the adjournment is taken.&nbsp;&nbsp;At an adjourned meeting, any business may be transacted which might have been transacted at the meeting as originally scheduled.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In the event there are not sufficient votes for a quorum, or to approve or ratify any matter being presented at the time of this Annual Meeting, the Annual Meeting may be adjourned in order to permit the further solicitation of proxies.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">VOTING</font><a name="VotingSecuritiesandPrincipalStockholders"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"> SECURITIES AND PRINCIPAL STOCKHOLDERS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The only class of voting securities of the Corporation is its Common Stock, $.10 par value ("Common Stock"), each share of which entitles the holder thereof to one vote except in the election of directors, where votes may be cumulated as described herein. Only stockholders of record at the close of business on </font><font style="display: inline;">March&nbsp;1, 2018</font><font style="display: inline;"> are entitled to notice of and to vote at the meeting. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		<p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">VOTING PROC</font><a name="VotingProceduresandMethodsofCountingVote"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">EDURES AND METHODS OF COUNTING VOTES</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">As to Proposal 1 regarding the election of directors, the proxy card being provided by the Board enables a stockholder to vote &#x201C;For&#x201D; the election of the </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">six</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> nominees proposed by the Board or to &#x201C;Withhold Authority&#x201D; to vote for the nominees being proposed. As discussed under Proposal 1, cumulative voting applies to the election of directors. Directors are elected by a plurality of the votes cast, without regard to either broker non-votes or proxies as to which the authority to vote for the nominee is withheld.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">As to Proposal</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">s</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">4</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, a stockholder may: (1) vote &#x201C;For&#x201D; the item, (2) vote &#x201C;Against&#x201D; the item, or (3) &#x201C;Abstain&#x201D; from voting on </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">the</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> item. In or</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">der to approve Proposals 2 and 4</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, each proposal must receive the affirmative vote of a majority of the shares voting on each matter at the annual meeting without regard to either shares as to which the &#x201C;Abstain&#x201D; box is ma</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">rked or broker non-votes. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Proposal 3 requires the affirmative vote of the holders of at least seventy percent (70%) of the outstanding shares of Common Stock of the Corporation entitled to vote to approve the proposed amendment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Abstentions and shares not voted by brokers and other entities holding shares on behalf of the beneficial owners will have the same effect as a vote against Proposal 3.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Proxies solicited hereby will be returned to the Corporation, tabulated by the Corporation&#x2019;s registrar and transfer agent and reviewed by the inspectors of election designated by the Board.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">2</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">PR</font><a name="Proposal1"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">OPOSAL 1</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">ELECTION OF DIRECTORS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Board of</font><font style="display: inline;"> the Corporation currently consists of eleven members. </font><font style="display: inline;">The Board has nominated Paul T. Canarick, Alexander L. Cover, Stephen V. Murphy, Peter Quick and Eric J. Tveter as the Class II directors for re-election and Denise Strain for election as a Class II director.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each Board member and nominee</font><font style="display: inline;">, with the exception of Michael N. Vittorio, who serves as President and Chief Executive Officer (&#x201C;CEO&#x201D;) of the Corporation and its wholly owned bank subsidiary, The First National Bank of Long Island (&#x201C;Bank&#x201D;), is independent as defined in the Nasdaq Rules.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Board is divided into two classes, Class I and Class II. The following table sets forth the present compos</font><font style="display: inline;">ition of the Board</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">

				<td valign="bottom" style="width:11.82%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;">
					<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
						<font style="display: inline;">2018</font></p>
				</td>
				<td valign="bottom" style="width:25.08%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;">

			</tr>

				<td valign="bottom" style="width:25.22%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;">

				</td>

		</table></div>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">As to the election of directors, each stockholder entitled to vote has the right to vote, in person or by proxy, the number of shares owned by him or her for as many persons as there are directors to be elected.&nbsp;&nbsp;A stockholder may also cumulate his or her votes by giving one candidate as many votes as the number of directors to be elected multiplied by the number of his or her shares </font><font style="display: inline;">or</font><font style="display: inline;"> by evenly distributing such votes on the same principle among any number of candidates.&nbsp;&nbsp;Cumulative voting can affect the election of directors if there are more nominees for director than positions to be filled.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event that cumulative voting is in effect, it is the intention of the proxies to vote cumulatively for the nominees listed, and if authority for any nominee or nominees is withheld, the votes will be distributed among the remaining candidates at</font><font style="display: inline;"> the discretion of the Board.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">It is intended that shares represented by properly executed proxies will be voted at the meeting in accordance with the </font><font style="display: inline;">instructions</font><font style="display: inline;"> indicated thereon and, in the absence of contrary indication, for the re-election of </font><font style="display: inline;">d</font><font style="display: inline;">irectors Canarick, Cover, Murphy, Quick and </font><font style="display: inline;">Tveter and for the election of d</font><font style="display: inline;">irector Strain.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each of the Class II directors will hold office until the 2020 Annual Meeting of Stockholders or until his or her successor is elected and qualified.&nbsp;&nbsp;If at the time of the 2018 Annual Meeting any of the nominees named above is unavailable or chooses not to serve as a director (an event that the Board does not now anticipate), the proxies will be voted for the election as director of such other person or persons as the Board may designate.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">The Board of Directors recommends a vote FOR all named nominees.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The following table sets forth a brief description of the business experience during the past five years of each of the nominees and Board members continuing in office.&nbsp;&nbsp;It also indicates any other directorships held during the past five years in any company with a class of securities registered pursuant to section 12 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 (&#x201C;1934 Act&#x201D;) or subject to the requirements of section 15(d) of the 1934 Act or any company registered as an investment company under the Investment Company Act of 1940.&nbsp;&nbsp;The year set forth for each director is the year in which the person named became a director of the Corporation and the Bank with the exception of Mr. Hogan, who became a director of the Corporation upon its </font><font style="display: inline;">formation</font><font style="display: inline;"> in 1984.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Diversity</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">The Governance and Nominating Committee believes that the Board as a whole should adequately reflect the diversity of the Company&#x2019;s constituencies and the communities in which the Company conducts business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although the Committee considers diversity in identifying nominees for director, it does not have a formal policy in this regard.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee has a broad view of diversity, and conceptualizes it to include differences of viewpoint, professional experience, education, skill and other individual qualities and attributes that contribute to board heterogeneity, as well as race, ethnicity, gender, and other characteristics.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Specific Core Competencies</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">In addition to general qualifications and the consideration of diversity, the Governance and Nominating Committee has developed a Skill Sets Matrix that sets forth the specific core competencies it believes one or more Board members should possess.&nbsp;&nbsp;The matrix is used to evaluate the collective skills of the existing Board and identify the skills that the Committee should seek when filling a Board vacancy or increasing the size of the Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Governance and Nominating Committee recognizes that some Board members may possess many of the core competencies, while others will possess only a few, but that each Board member should have particular strength with respect to at least one.&nbsp;&nbsp;The identified core competencies, which are subject to change from time to time, include, but are not limited to: corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and/or business operations, accounting and reporting, finance and/or investments, technology and/or information security, mergers and acquisitions, legal and/or regulatory, real estate, marketing and/or public relations and financial accounting experience necessary to qualify as an &#x201C;audit committee financial expert&#x201D; as defined in Regulation S-K of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;).</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">With respect to each of the </font><font style="display: inline;">Corporation</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2019;s directors, the narrative that follows sets forth the specific experience, qualifications, </font><font style="display: inline;">attributes</font><font style="display: inline;"> and skills that led to the conclusion that the person should serve as a director considering the Company&#x2019;s business and structure and the general qualifications and core competencies identified and deemed desirable by the Governance and Nominating Committee.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Paul T. Canarick - </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Canarick joined the Board in 1992 and is a member of the Governance and Nominating, Loan and Asset Liability Committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Canarick is President and Principal of Paul Todd, Inc., a privately held construction company.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. </font><font style="display: inline;">Canarick&#x2019;s</font><font style="display: inline;"> experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include banking, business leadership, organizational management and business operations and real estate.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Alexander L. Cover - </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Cover joined the Board in 2003 and is Chairman of the Audit Committee and a member of the Governance and Nominating and Asset Liability Committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;He is currently a business and management consultant in private practice and, among other things, assists privately held companies with developing business plans.&nbsp;&nbsp;Previously he was Partner-In-Charge of the financial institutions practice of the Long Island office of Ernst &amp; Young LLP.&nbsp;&nbsp;At Ernst &amp; Young, Mr. Cover&#x2019;s </font><font style="display: inline;">experience</font><font style="display: inline;"> also included, among other things, serving as review partner on both SEC and non-SEC engagements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Cover has also been a director of a number of not-for-profit entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Cover&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, accounting and reporting, finance, mergers and acquisitions, legal and regulatory.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">John J. Desmond - </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Desmond joined the Board in 2016 and is a member of the Audit and Compensation Committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;Previously he was Partner-In-Charge of the Long Island office of Grant Thornton LLP from 1988 through his retirement from the firm in 2015, having served over 40 years in the public accounting industry.&nbsp;&nbsp;At Grant Thornton, Mr. Desmond&#x2019;s experience also included, among </font><font style="display: inline;">other</font><font style="display: inline;"> things, serving as lead audit partner for </font><font style="display: inline;">many public and privately-held companies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Desmond was elected by the U.S. Partners of Grant Thornton LLP to be a Partnership Board Member from 2001 through 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board was responsible for oversight of many of the firm&#x2019;s activities including strategic planning, the performance of the senior leadership team and financial performance.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Desmond also serves as a director of a publicly held company, and serves or has served as a board member of a number of not-for-profit entities.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Desmond&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, accounting and reporting, finance, mergers and acquisitions, legal and regulatory.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Howard Thomas Hogan, Jr., Esq. - </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Hogan joined the Board in 1978 and is a member of the Loan and Governance and Nominating Committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Hogan is currently an attorney in private practice, with an emphasis on real estate.&nbsp;&nbsp;He currently serves and has served as a </font><font style="display: inline;">director</font><font style="display: inline;"> of numerous not-for-profit and community organizations.&nbsp;&nbsp;His experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, legal, real estate and public relations.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Stephen V. Murphy - </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Murphy joined the Board in 2005 and is Chairman of the Asset Liability Committee and a member of the Compensation and Loan Committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;He is currently President of S.V. Murphy &amp; Co., a financial advisory firm.&nbsp;&nbsp;He also serves as a director of several registered investment companies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Murphy&#x2019;s experience includes Merrill Lynch Capital Markets, where he was Managing </font><font style="display: inline;">Director</font><font style="display: inline;"> in the Investment Banking Department in charge of the Financial Institutions Mergers and Acquisitions Group.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to that, Mr. Murphy was with The First Boston Corporation as Managing Director in the Corporate Finance Department in charge of the Commercial Banking Group for Financing and Strategic Services.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Murphy also serves or has served as a director for various publicly held and not-for-profit entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Murphy&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, accounting and reporting, finance and investments and mergers and acquisitions.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Peter Quick</font><font style="display: inline;"> - Mr. Quick joined the Board in 2015 and is Chairman of the Loan Committee and a member of the Audit and Governance and Nominating Committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Quick has over 30 years of experience in the securities and financial services industries.&nbsp;&nbsp;He is a recognized leader in the securities industry with experience in the domestic and international equity markets, equities market making, market structure reform, trading technology and clearing operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Quick is a Partner of Burke and Quick Partners Holdings LLP, the parent company of Burke &amp; Quick Partners LLC, a broker dealer.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Quick was President of the American Stock Exchange from 2000 to 2005.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to joining the American Stock Exchange, he served as President of Quick &amp; Reilly Inc., a Quick &amp; Reilly subsidiary and a national discount brokerage firm.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Quick also serves or has served as a director of a number of publicly held companies and not-for-profit entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Quick&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, accounting and reporting, finance and investments, technology and information security, mergers and acquisitions, legal and regulatory and real estate.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Denise Strain</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">-</font><font style="display: inline;"> Ms. Strain joined the Board in 2017</font><font style="display: inline;"> and is a member of the Governance and Nominating and Loan Committees</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Strain has 35 years of experience in the banking industry including most recently as the Managing Director and Senior Tax Counsel of Citigroup Inc.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Strain currently serves as a member of the Board of Trustees of a not-for-profit educational institution.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Strain&#x2019;s experience has provided her with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, accounting and reporting, finance, mergers and acquisitions, legal and regulatory. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Milbrey Rennie Taylor - </font><font style="display: inline;">Ms. Taylor joined the Board in 2008 and is Chair of the Governance and Nominating Committee and a member of the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Taylor&#x2019;s experience includes over thirty years in the television news business.&nbsp;&nbsp;She served as Executive Producer of CBS News Sunday Morning and CBS Weekend News.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Taylor also served as Vice President of ThirdAge </font><font style="display: inline;">Media</font><font style="display: inline;">, an Internet company partly owned by CBS, Inc.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Taylor serves and has served as a director of a number of not-for-profit entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Taylor&#x2019;s experience has provided her with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, marketing and public relations. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Walter C. Teagle III -</font><font style="display: inline;"> Mr. Teagle joined the Board in 1996, became Chairman of the Board in 2005 and is an ex officio member for all purposes of all Board committees of the Corporation and the Bank.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle is currently President and owner of Teagle Management, Inc., a private investment firm, Chairman and Director of The Teagle Foundation, Inc. and Managing General Partner of Gulo Capital Partners L.P., a private investment partnership.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle&#x2019;s past experience includes a variety of executive and board positions including Managing Director, Groton Partners LLC, a merchant banking firm; Officer and Managing Director, Groton Asset Management LLC, an </font><font style="display: inline;">investment</font><font style="display: inline;"> management company; Executive Vice President and Director, Lexent, Inc., a publicly-held infrastructure service provider; and President, Chief Executive Officer, and Director, Metro Design Systems, Inc., an engineering design services firm.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle has also been a director of not-for-profit entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Teagle&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, finance and investments, technology and information security, and mergers and acquisitions. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Eric J. Tveter -</font><font style="display: inline;"> Mr. Tveter joined the Board in 2013 and is Chairman of the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;He is currently Chief Executive Officer, Central Europe Group, Liberty Global plc.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to that he was Chief Executive Officer of Liberty Global&#x2019;s Swiss and Austrian Region and Chief Executive Officer of upc cablecom GmbH of Switzerland, a Liberty Global company.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Tveter has extensive knowledge and experience in the US, UK and European cable industries.&nbsp;&nbsp;He was President of UK cable operator Telewest Global Inc. and held a range of senior management positions at Time Warner Cable, Comcast Corporation and Cablevision Systems Corporation.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Tveter was a Non-Executive Board Member of Open TV and served as Chairman of Sightspeed Inc., a video conferencing and communications provider.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Tveter&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, accounting and reporting, finance, technology and information security, mergers and acquisitions, real estate, marketing and public relations. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Michael N. Vittorio - </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Vittorio has been President and Chief Executive Officer of the Corporation and the Bank since 2003 and is a member of the Loan and Asset Liability Committees of the Bank.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to his employment by the Company in 2002, Mr. Vittorio was employed at J.P. Morgan Chase as Senior Vice President responsible for managing Chase Insurance Agency&#x2019;s Insurance Brokerage and Advisory Service Business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Previously he served in various capacities at J.P. Morgan Chase including Senior Credit Officer for Small </font><font style="display: inline;">Business</font><font style="display: inline;"> Financial Services, Middle Market Regional Manager and Division Executive in the Small Business/Commercial Division.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Vittorio also serves or has served as a director of a variety of not-for-profit entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Vittorio&#x2019;s experience has provided him with a number of the core competencies identified by the Governance and Nominating Committee, which include corporate governance, banking, strategic planning, business leadership, organizational management and business operations, mergers and acquisitions, real estate, marketing and public relations.&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">BOARD LE</font><a name="BoardLeadershipStructure"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">ADERSHIP STRUCTURE</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The </font><font style="display: inline;">Board</font><font style="display: inline;"> has determined that the Chairman of the Board will be an independent director.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board believes that stockholder interests are best served by having a Chairman of the Board who is independent of management and whose exclusive responsibility is the long-term best interest of the Corporation&#x2019;s stockholders.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Walter C. Teagle III has served as Chairman of the Board since May 2005.&nbsp;&nbsp;As Chairman, Mr. Teagle organizes the work of the Board and ensures that the Board has </font><font style="display: inline;">access</font><font style="display: inline;"> to sufficient information to enable it to carry out its functions, including monitoring the Corporation&#x2019;s performance and the performance of the Board and management.&nbsp;&nbsp;The role of the Chairman of the Board includes: (1) presiding over all meetings of the Board and stockholders, including regular executive sessions of the Board in which the Chief Executive Officer, a management director, and other members of management do not participate; (2) establishing the annual agenda of the Board and agendas of each meeting in consultation with the Chief Executive Officer; (3) serving as an ex officio member of each board committee and advising with respect to the work of each Board committee; (4) coordinating periodic Board reviews of </font>
		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">6</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">management&#x2019;s strategic plan for the Corporation; and (5) coordinating the Compensation Committee annual performance review of the Chief Executive Officer.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">BOARD&#x2019;S R</font><a name="BoardsRoleinRIskOversight"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">OLE IN RISK OVERSIGHT</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Risk is an integral part of Board and Board committee discussions.&nbsp;&nbsp;The significant risks facing the Corporation are set forth in an Enterprise Risk Management document.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation&#x2019;s management team, which includes a Chief Risk Officer, is responsible for identifying, assessing and managing risk and the Board is responsible for risk oversight and fulfills this responsibility primarily through its committees.&nbsp;&nbsp;In granting authority to management, approving policies and strategies and receiving management reports, the Board and its committees consider, among other things, the risks that the Corporation faces.&nbsp;&nbsp;For each critical risk, such as credit risk, interest rate risk, liquidity risk, and cybersecurity risk, the Corporation has a formal written policy that is approved by an appropriate Board committee or the full Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;As reflected in the Corporation&#x2019;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board and its committees address succession planning risk both in the ordinary course of business and on a contingent basis in case of unexpected events.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The following table sets forth the risk oversight responsibilities of the Board and Board committees.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>

						<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font></p>

				</td>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">MEETI</font><a name="MeetingsoftheBoardofDirectors"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">NGS OF THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">All of the members of the Board of the Corporation also serve on the Board of the Bank.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board of the Corporation held ten regular meetings during 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each director attended at least 75% of the aggregate number of Board meetings and meetings of the committees on which such director served. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">BOAR</font><a name="BoardCommitteesandMeetings"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">D COMMITTEES AND MEETINGS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Board of the Corporation has three standing committees: the Governance and Nominating Committee; the Audit Committee; and the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board of the Bank also has two standing committees: the Loan Committee and the Asset Liability Committee.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Governance and Nominating Committee</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">All the members of the Corporation&#x2019;s Governance and Nominating Committee are independent directors as defined in the Nasdaq Rules.&nbsp;&nbsp;The members of the Governance and Nominating Committee are Paul T. Canarick, Alexander L. Cover, Howard Thomas Hogan, Jr., Peter Quick</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> Denise Strain,</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Milbrey Rennie Taylor and Walter C. Teagle III.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committ</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">ee met five times during 2017.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The Corporation&#x2019;s Board has adopted a formal written charter for the Governance and Nominating Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;A current copy of the charter and the Corporation&#x2019;s Corporate Governance Guidelines are available on the Corporation&#x2019;s website by going to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">www.FNBLI.com</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">placing the cursor over &#x201C;Investor Relations,&#x201D; then clicking on &#x201C;Corporate Governance&#x201D; and then clicking on &#x201C;Board Governance and Nominating Committee Charter&#x201D; or &#x201C;Corporate Governance Guidelines.&#x201D;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Among other things, the Governance and Nominating Committee is currently responsible for: (1) maintaining the director succession plan; (2) identifying individuals qualified to become Board members and recommending to the Board the director nominees for the next annual meeting of stockholders; (3) </font><font style="display: inline;">recommending to the Board written corporate governance guidelines and monitoring compliance with said guidelines; (4) leading the Board in an annual Board self-assessment and reporting to the Board on its own self-assessment and the self-assessments performed by the other Board committees; (5) recommending to the Board, director candidates for each committee; and (6) establishing the director skill sets matrix to evaluate the collective skills of the existing board and to identify skills that may be sought when filling vacancies.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Although the Corporation has a long history of being able to attract and maintain a cohesive Board with the variety of skills necessary to oversee the affairs of the Corporation, the Governance and Nominating Committee will consider director candidates recommended by stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;Submission of candidates may be made in writing at any time.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, to be considered by the Governance and Nominating Committee for nomination at the 2019 annual meeting, such submissions should be made no later than December 14, 2018 to the Chair of the Governance and Nominating Committee at the Corporation&#x2019;s address set forth in this proxy statement.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, nominations for the election of directors may be made by any stockholder entitled to vote for the election of directors provided that such nominations are made in accordance with the provisions of the Corporation&#x2019;s bylaws establishing the information and notice requirements for such nominations. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">In addition to interviews, the Governance and Nominating Committee may evaluate potential nominees by reviewing resumes, checking business and/or personal references, and performing background checks as deemed appropriate.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation has not paid a fee to any third party or parties to assist in identifying or evaluating potential nominees.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Except for Ms. Strain who was appointed by the Board effective December 1, 2017, all of the Class II nominees approved by the Governance and Nominating Committee for inclusion on the Corporation&#x2019;s proxy card for the Annual Meeting of Stockholders to be held April 17, 2018 are directors standing for re-election.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Strain&#x2019;s introduction to the Board was based on the recommendation of a retired non-management director.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Audit Committee</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The members of the Audit Committee are Alexander L. Cover, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">John J. Desmond, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">Peter Quick and Walter C. Teagle III.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee met eight times during 2017.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Calibri;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The Corporation&#x2019;s Board has adopted a formal written charter for the Audit Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;A current copy of the charter is available on the Corporation&#x2019;s website by going to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">www.FNBLI.com</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">placing the cursor over &#x201C;Investor Relations,&#x201D; then clicking on &#x201C;Corporate Governance&#x201D; and then clicking on &#x201C;Board Audit Committee Charter.&#x201D;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Board has determined that all members of the Audit Committee are independent as independence for audit committee members is defined in SEC Rule 10A-3 and the Nasdaq Rules.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board has also determined that Alexander L. Cover and John J. Desmond each qualify as an &#x201C;audit committee financial expert&#x201D; as that term is defined in Item 407 of Regulation S-K of the Securities and Exchange Commission.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board has also determined that all members of the Audit Committee have banking or related financial management expertise.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The responsibilities of the Audit Committee are described under the heading &#x201C;Audit Committee Report&#x201D; in this proxy statement.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Compensation Committee </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">All the members of the Corporation&#x2019;s Compensation Committee are independent directors as defined in the Nasdaq Rules.&nbsp;&nbsp;The members of the Compensation Committee are John J. Desmond, Stephen V. Murphy, Milbrey Rennie Taylor, Walter C. Teagle III and Eric J. Tveter.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee met seven times during 2017.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Calibri;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">The Corporation&#x2019;s Board has adopted a formal written charter for the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;A current copy of the charter is available on the Corporation&#x2019;s website by going to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">www.FNBLI.com</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">placing the cursor over &#x201C;Investor Relations,&#x201D; then clicking on &#x201C;Corporate Governance&#x201D; and then clicking on &#x201C;Board Compensation Committee Charter.&#x201D;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Among other things, the Compensation Committee is responsible for: (1) implementing and maintaining guiding principles, compensation policies and compensation plans for the CEO, other executive officers and non-management directors and reporting and making recommendations to the Board with respect thereto taking into account market competitive data; (2) recommending to the Board approval of employment agreements for the CEO and other executive officers;&nbsp;&nbsp;(3) evaluating the performance of the CEO against established goals and objectives and approving for Board ratification the base salary level for the CEO subject to any existing employment agreement; (4) reviewing the CEO&#x2019;s performance evaluation of the other executive officers of the Corporation and approving for Board ratification the base salary level of each such officer subject to any existing employment agreements; (5) approving for Board ratification cash incentives and bonuses to the CEO and other executive officers pursuant to the Corporation&#x2019;s incentive compensation plans or otherwise;&nbsp;&nbsp;(6) setting corporate goals, objectives and compensation plans used to determine cash incentives and bonuses paid to the CEO and other executive officers and equity compensation awarded to the CEO, other executive officers and non-management</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">directors; (7) approving for Board ratification awards of equity compensation to the CEO, other executive officers and non-management directors pursuant to the Corporation&#x2019;s equity compensation plans or</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">otherwise; (8) recommending to the Board compensation proposals such as the compensation to be paid to the Corporation&#x2019;s NEOs, say-on-pay, say-when-on-pay or equity incentive plans to be included in the Corporation&#x2019;s annual proxy statement; (9) reviewing the overall annual salary budget for the Bank&#x2019;s entire employee population; (10) conducting, or causing to be conducted, at its discretion, a periodic review of the Corporation&#x2019;s pension, 401(k), supplemental executive retirement and health and welfare plans; (11) reviewing and approving the compensation discussion and analysis included in the Corporation&#x2019;s annual proxy statement and preparing or causing to be prepared the Compensation Committee Report to be included therein; (12) reviewing executive management&#x2019;s determination of compensation of non-executive officers of the Corporation including the total amount of incentive compensation to be paid to such officers; and (13) considering the results of the most recent non-binding, stockholder advisory vote on executive compensation and, if deemed necessary, recommending to the Board changes in compensation policies, practices and decisions.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Compensation Committee administers the Corporation&#x2019;s equity incentive plan, including selecting directors and officers to whom awards are to be made and determining the timing, duration, amount, type and terms of each award.&nbsp;&nbsp;Members of the Compensation Committee as well as all other non-employee directors of the Corporation have been eligible for awards of stock-based compensation in the past and it is currently anticipated that they will be eligible for future awards.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">8</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">In determining an appropriate level of compensation for the CEO, other executive officers and the Board, the Compensation Committee periodically engages an independent compensation consulting firm to gather and help analyze the information necessary to make such determinations.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2017, the Compensation Committee engaged Pearl Meyer &amp; Partners (&#x201C;PM&amp;P&#x201D;), an independent national compensation consulting firm, to conduct a review of the compensation of the Company&#x2019;s CEO, other executive officers and the Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;The objective of the review was to provide an assessment of the competitiveness and effectiveness of the Corporation&#x2019;s compensation programs relative to peer banks. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In performing their review, PM&amp;P worked with the Compensation Committee to develop a custom peer group.&nbsp;&nbsp;The peer banks </font><font style="display: inline;">a</font><font style="display: inline;">re similar in size and scope to the Bank, with average total assets of approximately $4.1 billion.&nbsp;&nbsp;This average compares to total assets for the Bank of approximately $3.9 billion at year-end 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;The peer group consist</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> of eighteen (18) publicly-held bank holding companies located in the Bank&#x2019;s general geographic area and include</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> Arrow Financial Corporation, Bridge Bancorp, Inc., Brookline Bancorp, Inc., Bryn Mawr Bank Corporation, Century Bancorp, Inc., CNB Financial Corporation, ConnectOne Bancorp, Inc., Financial Institutions, Inc., First Connecticut Bancorp, Inc., Flushing Financial Corporation, Lakeland Bancorp, Inc., Northfield Bancorp, Inc., OceanFirst Financial Corp., Peapack-Gladstone Financial Corporation, Sun Bancorp, Inc., TrustCo Bank Corp NY, Univest Corporation of Pennsylvania and Washington Trust Bancorp, Inc.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to gathering and analyzing compensation data for the peer group, PM&amp;P also gathered and analyzed peer compensation data from published industry surveys, including their own survey and surveys performed by the American Bankers Association and other nationally recognized compensation consulting firms.&nbsp;&nbsp;In performing their reviews, PM&amp;P assessed total remuneration and the individual elements of total remuneration including base salary, annual cash incentive compensation, annual equity awards, retirement benefits and perquisites.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on their reviews, PM&amp;P provided the Compensation Committee with a comparison of the compensation of the CEO and other executive officers to the market 10</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;">, 25</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;">, 50</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;">, 75</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th </font><font style="display: inline;">and 90</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;"> percentiles.&nbsp;&nbsp;PM&amp;P also assessed the elements of Board compensation both individually and in the aggregate, including annual retainers, meeting-based fees and fees for chair roles and special meetings.&nbsp;&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In addition to the services described above, PM&amp;P was also engaged to perform a review of the structural elements of the Corporation&#x2019;s executive incentive plan.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">The Compensation Committee received a letter from PM&amp;P regarding its independence under the six factors to be considered for such purposes under Nasdaq Rules, assessed the independence of PM&amp;P pursuant to such rules and determined that PM&amp;P is an independent and conflict-free advisor to the Corporation.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Compensation Committee considers the most recent stock</font><font style="display: inline;">holder say-on-pay advisory vote</font><font style="display: inline;"> in reviewing the Corporation&#x2019;s executive compensation policies, practices and decisions.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee concluded that no significant revisions were necessary to our executive compensation program as a result of the most recent say-on-pay advisory vote.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:18pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Compensation Committee Interlocks and Insider Participation</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">.</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;No member of the Compensation Committee: (1) was an officer or employee of the Corporation or the Bank; (2) was formerly an officer of the Corporation or the Bank; or (3) had any relationship requiring disclosure by the Corporation under the SEC&#x2019;s rules governing disclosure of related party transactions.&nbsp; No executive officer of the Corporation served as a director or member of a compensation committee of another entity, one of whose executive officers served as a member of the Corporation&#x2019;s Board or Compensation Committee.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Loan Committee of the Bank </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The members of the Loan Committee are Paul T. Canarick, Howard Thomas Hogan, Jr., Stephen V. Murphy, Peter Quick, </font><font style="display: inline;">Denise Strain, </font><font style="display: inline;">Walter C. Teagle III and Michael N. Vittorio.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee met four times during 2017.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Loan Committee is responsible for providing oversight with respect to the Bank&#x2019;s lending activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;In this regard, the Committee: (1) oversees credit risk and approves policies that govern lending activities and credit risk management; (2) reviews and ratifies the allowance for loan and lease losses; (3) reviews and approves specific loan transactions where required by policy; and (4) reviews reports from management, internal auditors, the internal loan review function and regulators related to lending activities and credit risk. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Asset Liability Committee of the Bank</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The members of the Asset Liability Committee are Paul T. Canarick, Alexander L. Cover, Stephen V. Murphy, Walter C. Teagle III and Michael N. Vittorio.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committ</font><font style="display: inline;">ee met four times during 2017.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Asset Liability Committee is responsible for providing oversight with respect to the Bank&#x2019;s achievement of its overall objective of optimizing returns consistent with prudent risk management regarding assets, liabilities, equity and off-balance sheet activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;In this regard, the Committee: (1) oversees investment risk and approves the investment policy limits and operating guidelines set forth in the Bank&#x2019;s Investment Policy; (2) oversees the Bank&#x2019;s investment in and management of bank-owned life insurance and approves the pre-purchase, ongoing monitoring and other requirements set forth in the Bank&#x2019;s Bank-Owned Life Insurance Policy; (3) oversees interest rate risk and approves the risk limits and operating guidelines set forth in the Bank&#x2019;s Interest Rate Risk Policy; (4) oversees liquidity risk and approves the risk limits and operating guidelines set forth in the Bank&#x2019;s Liquidity Policy and Liquidity Contingency Plan; and (5) oversees management&#x2019;s use, if any, of embedded and stand-alone derivative instruments for purposes of managing interest rate risk.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">9</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">BOARD MEMBER A</font><a name="BoardMemberAttendanceatAnnualMeetings"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">TTENDANCE AT ANNUAL MEETINGS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Board strongly encourages each of its members to attend the Annual Meeting of Stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;In this regard, the Board sets the date for the Annual Meeting of Stockholders to coincide with its April Board meeting.&nbsp;&nbsp;All directors attended the prior year&#x2019;s Annual Meeting of Stockholders, which was held on April 19, 2017.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">SECURITY HOLDER C</font><a name="SecurityHolderCommunications"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">OMMUNICATIONS TO THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Corporation&#x2019;s Board does not have a formal process for security holders to send communications to the Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board believes that a formal process is unnecessary because the Corporation is relatively small and both the Chairman of the Board and the President and CEO, who is also a director, are easily accessible by telephone and mail.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">COMPENS</font><a name="CompensationofDirectors"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">ATION OF DIRECTORS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Cash Compensation</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The Chairman of the Board of the Corporation and the Bank receives an annual retainer for service on both boards.&nbsp;&nbsp;Non-employee directors of the Corporation receive an annual retainer for service on both boards for attending up to ten meetings per year and a per meeting fee for each meeting in excess of ten.&nbsp;&nbsp;Annual retainers and per meeting fees for service on both boards in 2017 are shown in the following table.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>

				</td>

					<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
