						<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">117,183</font></p>
				</td>
				<td valign="bottom" style="width:25.00%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt solid #000000 ;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;border-right:1pt solid #000000 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;">
					<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
						<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">206,240</font></p>
				</td>
			</tr>
		</table></div>
		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;text-indent:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In the future the Compensation Committee may use different metrics to measure corporate performance such as earnings per share, return on average stockholders&#x2019; equity or the efficiency ratio, or may change the weights applied to each metric.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The Compensation Committee believes that total target remuneration for executive officers should be market competitive, benchmarked to the 50</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> percentile of the Bank&#x2019;s peer group and take into consideration individual and corporate performance and tenure.&nbsp;&nbsp;In performing their 2017 review of executive compensation, PM&amp;P compiled compensation data from the proxy statements of the Corporation&#x2019;s custom peer group and from published industry surveys and, based on this data, calculated percentile amounts against which total compensation for the Company&#x2019;s NEOs could be compared.&nbsp;&nbsp;The PM&amp;P study showed that total target compensation for all NEOs ranged from the 19</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to the 54</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> percentile. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">17</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Termination and Change in Control Payments</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Each of the NEOs has an employment agreement with the Corporation that provides for severance compensation in the event that the executive is terminated by the Board without cause or terminates his employment for Good Reason, as defined, whether or not such termination occurs in connection with a change in control (see Employment Agreements section of this proxy statement).&nbsp;&nbsp;These provisions are designed to insure, among other things, that the NEOs are not significantly harmed or unduly enriched and are therefore objective with respect to the consummation of a transaction, such as a sale or merger of the Bank that may be in the best interests of the Corporation&#x2019;s stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;In determining the severance arrangement for the CEO and each of the other NEOs, the Compensation Committee considered the severance arrangements offered by peer banks to their NEOs.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Impact of Accounting and Tax Treatment of Certain Elements of Compensation</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Compensation Committee has granted non-qualified stock options (&#x201C;NQSOs&#x201D;) and RSUs as equity compensation.&nbsp;&nbsp;NQSOs and RSUs are advantageous from the Corporation&#x2019;s standpoint because the Corporation records a book tax benefit for the compensation cost recognized for financial statement reporting purposes under FASB ASC Topic 718 and receives a tax benefit upon the exercise of in-the-money NQSOs and the vesting of RSUs.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Tax Deductibility of Executive Compensation</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Internal Revenue Code Section 162(m) limits the tax deductibility of compensation paid to any covered employee to $1 million per year.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (the &#x201C;Act&#x201D;) was signed into law on December 22, 2017 and amends Section 162(m) to treat all NEOs as covered employees (previously the CFO was not a covered employee) and to eliminate the exclusion of qualified performance-based compensation in determining compensation subject to the $1 million limitation.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, the Act provides &#x201C;grandfathered&#x201D; treatment for qualified performance-based compensation in excess of $1 million that meets the requirements of Section 162(m), is payable pursuant to a written binding contract in effect as of November 2, 2017 and is not modified in any material respect.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that most of the compensation paid to the NEOs as a group through year-end 2017 was deductible under the applicable provisions of Section 162(m).&nbsp;&nbsp;A number of requirements must be met for particular compensation to qualify for tax deductibility, so there can be no assurance that incentive compensation paid to the NEOs will be fully deductible in all circumstances.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Compensation Committee will consider the impact of the Act on the design of our executive compensation programs going forward.&nbsp;&nbsp;While the Compensation Committee does not have a formal policy with respect to the payment of compensation in excess of the deduction limit under Code Section 162(m), the Compensation Committee&#x2019;s practice is to structure compensation programs offered to the NEOs with a view towards maximizing tax deductibility of amounts paid.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, in structuring compensation programs, the Compensation Committee considers a variety of factors, including the Corporation&#x2019;s tax position, the materiality of the payments and tax deductions involved and the need for flexibility to address unforeseen circumstances.&nbsp;&nbsp;After considering these factors, the Compensation Committee may decide to authorize payments, all or part of which may be nondeductible for federal income tax purposes.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Role of Executive Officers In Determining Executive Compensation</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Compensation Committee approves the proposed compensation of executive officers after considering, among other things, executive compensation studies periodically performed by independent compensation consulting firms.&nbsp;&nbsp;From time to time, the Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer have served as a resource to the Compensation Committee in gathering the information necessary to make such compensation determinations.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, these officers do not have a policy-making role with respect to determining the amount or form of executive compensation and do not participate in Compensation Committee deliberations regarding their own compensation.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Compensation Policies and Practices As They Relate To Risk Management</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Corporation has a written incentive-based compensation policy that sets forth governance roles for the Compensation Committee, senior management and the Corporation&#x2019;s internal auditors.&nbsp;&nbsp;The policy is reviewed annually by the Compensation Committee, modified if deemed appropriate and approved.&nbsp;&nbsp;The purpose of the policy is to ensure that the Corporation&#x2019;s incentive-based compensation arrangements, or any feature of any such arrangement, do not encourage executive officers or employees to: (1) expose the Corporation to inappropriate risks by providing such persons with excessive compensation, fees or benefits; or (2) take inappropriate risks that could lead to material financial loss to the Corporation.&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant to this policy, the Corporation&#x2019;s incentive-based compensation arrangements are required to: (1) balance risk and financial rewards, through such things as risk adjustments of awards, deferral of payments, longer performance periods and/or reduced sensitivity to short-term performance; (2) be compatible with effective internal controls and risk management; and (3) be supported by strong corporate governance, including active and effective oversight by the Compensation Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee has determined that the Company&#x2019;s compensation policies and practices for its employees, including non-executive officers, are not reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on the Company.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">18</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Stock Ownership Guidelines and Equity Award Retention Policy</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">As a condition to receiving equity awarded under the Corporation&#x2019;s equity incentive plan each director and executive officer shall enter into an agreement with the Company providing that any stock acquired from the exercise of stock options or the vesting of equity awards, net of the disposition of shares for tax withholding requirements, must be held until stock ownership requirements are met.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Each director of the Corporation is required to have beneficial ownership of shares of Common Stock of the Corporation with a current market value equal to three (3) times cash retainers, which includes Committee retainers and per meeting fees.&nbsp;&nbsp;The CEO of the Corporation is required to have beneficial ownership of shares of common stock of the Corporation with a current market value equal to three (3) times his or her current base salary.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each other executive officer of the Corporation is required to have beneficial ownership of shares of common stock of the Corporation with a current market value equal to one (1) times his or her current base salary.&nbsp;&nbsp;All ownership requirements need to be met as follows: (1) within five years of becoming a director or executive officer; (2) within five years of an increase in ownership requirements for the incremental increase only; or (3) within three years of falling out of compliance with these requirements due to compensation increases or fluctuations in market value.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Clawback Policy</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Corporation has a clawback policy to enable the Company to recover any bonus or incentive compensation awarded or paid to the Company&#x2019;s executive officers if: (1) the payments or awards were based on materially inaccurate financial statements or any other materially inaccurate performance metric, and (2) the amount of the incentive compensation, as calculated under restated financial results, is less than the amount actually paid or awarded under the original financial results.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Anti-Hedging Policy</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Directors, NEOs, other officers and employees are prohibited from hedging the Corporation&#x2019;s securities with the use of financial instruments (including prepaid variable forward contracts, equity swaps, calls, puts, collars, and exchange funds) that offset a decrease in the market value of the Company&#x2019;s equity securities and any other transaction with comparable economic consequences.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Shareholder Advisory Vote on Compensation</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Compensation Committee considers the results of the annual say-on-pay stockholder advisory vote on the compensation paid to NEOs.&nbsp;&nbsp;To the extent there is a significant vote against the compensation paid to our NEOs, the Compensation Committee will consider our stockholders&#x2019; concerns and evaluate whether any actions are necessary to address those concerns.&nbsp;&nbsp;At the 2017 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, there was substantial support for the say-on-pay proposal.&nbsp;&nbsp;After a comprehensive market review and in light of strong stockholder support, the Compensation Committee concluded that no significant revisions were necessary to our executive compensation program.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">COMPENSAT</font><a name="CompensationofExecutiveOfficers"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">ION OF EXECUTIVE OFFICERS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The following table sets forth information with respect to the aggregate compensation paid, earned or awarded for the years ended December 31, 2017, 2016 and 2015 to the CEO, CFO and each of the additional three most highly compensated executive officers of the Bank.&nbsp;&nbsp;All compensation information is provided pursuant to the Securities and Exchange Commission executive compensation disclosure rules for proxy statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;All of the listed officers are also officers of the Corporation but received salaries only from the Bank. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%; table-layout: fixed;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt;">
			<p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:6pt 0pt;">
				<sup style="margin:6pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;text-decoration:none;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:none;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;;"> (1)</sup>
			</p>
		</td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top">
			<p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:6pt 0pt;">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The Bank has a legacy SERP for the CEO that is explained in the &#x201C;PENSION BENEFITS&#x201D; section of this proxy statement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The CEO&#x2019;s participation in the legacy SERP began upon his tenure as CEO of the Corporation and the Bank in 2004.&nbsp;&nbsp;Except for this one legacy SERP, the Board has adopted a prohibition of tax gross-up arrangements and has included this prohibition in the Corporation&#x2019;s published Corporate Governance Guidelines.</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The Compensation Committee believes that each named executive officer&#x2019;s total compensation is appropriately balanced between currently paid out and deferred compensation, with deferred compensation consisting of equity awards that vest over time and retirement benefits provided under the Corporation&#x2019;s 401(k), Pension and SERP plans.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">Pay Ratio</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Pursuant to Item 402(u) of Regulation S-K and Section 953(b) of the Dodd-Frank Act, presented below is the ratio of annual total compensation of the Corporation&#x2019;s CEO to the annual total compensation of the Corporation&#x2019;s median paid employee, excluding the CEO.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The ratio presented below is a reasonable estimate calculated in a manner consistent with Item 402(u).</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In identifying the Corporation&#x2019;s median paid employee, the Corporation utilized the year-to-date compensation of each full-time and part-time permanent employee from the twenty-sixth bi-weekly payroll of 2017 paid on December 22nd.&nbsp;&nbsp;There were no seasonal or temporary employees on that payroll.&nbsp;&nbsp;Compensation for this purpose includes regular earnings plus overtime, Saturday pay, commissions, cash incentives and stock-based compensation.&nbsp;&nbsp;The earnings of employees included on the December 22nd payroll that were employed for less than a full year in 2017 were converted to a twenty-six bi-weekly payroll equivalent. Full-time equivalent adjustments were not made.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:6pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The 2017 annual total compensation of our CEO and median paid employee was determined under Item 402 of Regulation S-K and was $1,669,209 and $59,360, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;The CEO&#x2019;s annual total compensation for 2017 was 28 times that of the annual total compensation for 2017 of the median paid employee. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">COMPENS</font><a name="CompensationPursuanToPlans"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">ATION PURSUANT TO PLANS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">Equity Incentive Plans </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The Corporation has awards outstanding under the 2006 Stock Compensation Plan (&#x201C;2006 Plan&#x201D;) and the 2014 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;Currently, awards can only be granted under the 2014 Plan, which was approved by the Corporation&#x2019;s stockholders on April 22, 2014 as a successor to the 2006 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2014 Plan gives the Board flexibility to attract and retain highly qualified officers and directors by offering a competitive compensation program.&nbsp;&nbsp;Equity awards align the interests of our directors and management with the interests of our stockholders by potentially increasing the ownership interests of directors and officers in our Common Stock.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Awards under the 2014 Plan may be granted as incentive and non-qualified stock options, stock appreciation rights, restricted stock awards, restricted stock units or any combination thereof.&nbsp;&nbsp;Substantially all awards granted under the 2014 Plan have been restricted stock units with performance or time-based vesting, while awards granted under the predecessor plan consisted of a combination of nonqualified stock options and restricted stock units.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The following table presents the number of shares of Common Stock to be issued upon the exercise of outstanding stock options and vesting of RSUs, and the number of shares of Common Stock remaining available for future issuance under the 2014 Plan, as of December 31, 2017, adjusted to reflect 72,128 RSUs granted in January 2018 based on 2017 performance.&nbsp;&nbsp;The table also presents the weighted average exercise price of outstanding stock options as of December 31, 2017.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt -459.35pt;text-indent:459.35pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>

			<font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">The Bank has a tax-qualified defined benefit pension plan and maintains the related SERP described hereinafter.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following table sets forth the present value of accumulated benefits under the Pension Plan as of December 31, 2017, under the pension portion of the SERP as of September 30, 2017, and the number of years of credited service for each named executive officer through December 31, 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;No pension benefits were distributed to the NEOs during 2017.</font>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%; table-layout: fixed;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt;">
			<p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;">
				<font style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;;"> (1)</font>
			</p>
		</td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top">
			<p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The actuarial assumptions used in determining the present value of the accumulated benefit for each named executive officer under the Pension Plan are set forth in Note J &#x201C;Retirement Plans&#x201D; to the Corporation&#x2019;s 2017 Consolidated Financial Statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;With respect to the SERP, the present value of the accumulated benefit is equal to the estimated purchase price of a deferred annuity on September 30, 2017 and starting at age 65.&nbsp; </font></p></td></tr></table></div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">Pension Plan</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">Employees, including the NEOs, who are over 21 years of age and have been employed by the Bank for more than one year, are eligible to participate in the Pension Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;Compensation used to determine benefits includes base salary, commissions, cash incentive compensation and taxable fringe benefits, but excludes employer contributions to the 401(k) Plan, amounts realized from the exercise of nonqualified stock options, amounts realized from the conversion of restricted stock units into shares of stock and amounts realized from the sale, exchange or other disposition of stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;Employees that elect to participate in the Pension Plan make contributions of 2% of their compensation used to determine benefits.&nbsp;&nbsp;Employees become fully vested in the Pension Plan after 5 years of service with the Bank and 4 years of participation in the Pension Plan (no vesting occurs during that 5-year period) or, for employees hired before February 28, 2011, upon attainment of age 55.&nbsp;&nbsp;The normal retirement age is 65.&nbsp;&nbsp;For benefits earned through February 28, 2011, early retirement with an unreduced benefit is available at age 62, provided that at least 10 years of vesting service had been completed by age 62 and employment by the Bank began at age 55 or prior.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early retirement with a reduced benefit is available beginning at age 55.&nbsp;&nbsp;For benefits earned through February 28, 2011, the reduction is equal to 3% per year for each year that early retirement precedes age 65, or age 62 provided that at least 10 years of vesting service have been completed by age 62 and employment began at age 55 or prior.&nbsp;&nbsp;For benefits earned after February 28, 2011, the reduction is based on actuarial equivalence.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Upon retirement, each participant with a spouse is paid a benefit in the form of a joint and survivor annuity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Participants without a spouse are paid a benefit in the form of a single life annuity guaranteed for sixty (60) months.&nbsp;&nbsp;All participants, whether with or without a spouse, may elect optional forms of benefit payments.&nbsp;&nbsp;For all participants, the annuity benefit is an amount equal to the sum of: (1) the participant&#x2019;s Average Annual Compensation multiplied by the product of 1.75 percent and the participant&#x2019;s credited years of service through February 28, 2011; plus (2) the participant&#x2019;s Average Annual Compensation multiplied by the product of 1.50 percent and the participant&#x2019;s credited years of service after February 28, 2011, with total years of credited service under clauses &#x201C;1&#x201D; and &#x201C;2&#x201D; limited to a maximum of 35 years; plus (3) 1.25 percent of Average Annual Compensation multiplied by the participant&#x2019;s credited years of service in excess of 35 years (up to five such years); and less (4) the product of 0.49 percent of the participant&#x2019;s Final Average Annual Compensation, limited to Covered Compensation, and the participant&#x2019;s Benefit Service up to 35 years.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 0.49 percent represents the minimum Social Security offset to the pension benefit.&nbsp;&nbsp;Average Annual Compensation, Final Average Annual Compensation, Covered Compensation and Benefit Service are all as defined in the Plan document.&nbsp;&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The Bank has a legacy SERP with the CEO as its only participant.&nbsp;&nbsp;The CEO&#x2019;s participation in this legacy plan began upon his tenure as CEO of the Corporation and the Bank in 2004.&nbsp;&nbsp;The SERP provides the additional benefits that would have been provided to the CEO under the Pension and 401(k) Plans in the absence of Internal Revenue Code limitations for qualified plans. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The SERP was also designed so that the supplemental pension and 401(k) contributions are made to a "secular trust" for the benefit of the CEO so that the assets are protected in the same manner as those of the Pension and 401(k) Plans (amounts contributed to the secular trust are not subject to the claims of creditors of the Bank).&nbsp;&nbsp;The Bank&#x2019;s contributions to the secular trust are tax-deductible by the Bank when made and, even though the SERP benefits will not be distributed to the CEO until a later time, such contributions and earnings thereon are taxable to the CEO when received or earned by the trust.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Bank&#x2019;s contributions to the SERP are reduced by applicable income tax withholdings.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of the foregoing, in lieu of increasing the Bank&#x2019;s contributions to the SERP or the CEOs other sources of compensation to take into account the taxes incurred by the CEO, the Bank contributes an amount to the SERP that, after applicable withholding taxes, will be sufficient to fund the SERP&#x2019;s benefit obligation when due.&nbsp;&nbsp;The assets in the secular </font>
		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">24</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		</p>

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">401(k) Plan</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The Bank has a tax-qualified 401(k) Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;Employees, including the NEOs, are eligible to participate provided they are at least 18 years of age.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Bank may, at its sole discretion, make matching contributions to each participant's account based on the amount of the participant's tax deferred contributions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Eligibility for employer matching contributions, if any, occurs after completing twelve (12) consecutive months of Eligibility Service, as defined, in which the participant worked a minimum of 1,000 hours.&nbsp;&nbsp;The sum of employee elective contributions and employer matching contributions plus any other additions to a participant&#x2019;s account for 2017 cannot exceed the lesser of $54,000 or 100% of the participant&#x2019;s compensation.&nbsp;&nbsp;Participants are fully vested in their elective contributions and fully vest in any employer matching contributions afte</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">r five years of participation. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Employer matching contributions made during the first five years of participation vest ratably over the remainder of the five-year period.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Participants in the 401(k) Plan will receive benefits generally upon attainment of age 65.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, the 401(k) Plan contains provisions allowing pre-termination withdrawals and loans under certain circumstances.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amount of a participant&#x2019;s Normal Retirement Benefit, as defined, will depend upon the accumulation of contributions and forfeitures and the investment performance of the 401(k) Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 401(k) Plan matching contributions for 2017 made to the account of each NEO are set forth in the &#x201C;All Other Compensation Table&#x201D; appearing elsewhere in this proxy statement.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="EmploymentAgreements"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">EMPLOYMENT </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">AGREEMENTS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The NEOs each have employment agreements with the Corporation pursuant to which Mr. Vittorio is employed as President and CEO of the Corporation, Mr. Curtis is employed as Senior Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer of the Corporation, Mr. Becker is employed as Executive Vice President and Chief Risk Officer of the Corporation, Mr. Kick is employed as Executive Vice President and Senior Retail Loan Officer of the Corporation and Mr. Daley is employed as Executive Vice President and Senior Commercial Banking Officer of the Corporation.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Mr. Vittorio&#x2019;s agreement has a term of three (3) years beginning January 1, 2017 and continuing through December 31, 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon written notice to Mr. Vittorio on or before January 1, 2019, the Board of the Corporation may extend Mr. Vittorio&#x2019;s employment agreement for an additional year through December 31, 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;During such extended period, Mr. Vittorio&#x2019;s position and related duties with the Corporation and the Bank may be modified by the Board to reflect the Board&#x2019;s determinations as to CEO succession planning, provided that Mr. Vittorio&#x2019;s base salary and benefits in effect immediately prior to the start of the extended period remain the same.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The other NEOs have agreements with a term of two (2) years beginning January 1, 2017 and extending through December 31, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;Commencing on January 1, 2018 and continuing on January 1 of each year thereafter (the &#x201C;Anniversary Date&#x201D;), the employment agreement with each of the other NEOs shall renew for an additional period of one year such that the remaining term shall be two years unless written notice of non-renewal is provided to the NEO at least thirty (30) days prior to any such Anniversary Date.&nbsp;&nbsp;Notwithstanding the foregoing, the employment agreement with each of the other NEOs shall expire on December 31 of the calendar year in which the NEO attains age 65 (&#x201C;Retirement Age Termination Date&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;Nothing in the employment agreements shall mandate or prohibit the employment of the other NEO&#x2019;s beyond their Retirement Age Termination Date.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, the other NEOs shall not be entitled to any benefits or payments under their employment agreements following the Retirement Age Termination Date unless the Corporation has elected to extend such agreements pursuant to their terms for an additional period of two years. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">25</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">Pursuant to each NEO&#x2019;s employment agreement, if the NEO is terminated by the Board without cause or the NEO terminates his employment following an event constituting Good Reason, the NEO will receive a cash lump sum severance payment equal to a multiple of the NEO&#x2019;s base salary (three times base salary for the CEO and two times base salary for the other NEOs) plus an amount equal to the product of the reasonably estimated monthly cost of the medical, dental and vision insurance coverage maintained by the Bank for the NEO immediately prior to the NEOs date of termination multiplied by thirty-six (36) for the CEO and twenty-four (24) for the other NEOs.&nbsp;&nbsp;The cash lump sum payment is conditioned on the NEO executing a release of the NEO&#x2019;s claims against the Corporation and any affiliate, and their officers, directors, successors and assigns.&nbsp;&nbsp;The CEO&#x2019;s cash lump sum payment is also conditioned on the CEO not being eligible to receive compensation and benefits pursuant to the CEO&#x2019;s employment agreement in connection with a change in control, as defined.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to receiving a cash lump sum payment, outstanding restricted stock units granted to the CEO shall become vested and payable under the same terms and conditions as would apply upon the CEO&#x2019;s retirement as set forth in the applicable award agreements between the Corporation and the CEO.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Upon termination of the CEO&#x2019;s employment by the Corporation without cause or by the CEO with Good Reason on or after the effective time of a change in control, as defined, the CEO shall receive a cash lump sum payment equal to three (3) times the sum of CEOs highest rate of base salary payable during the current calendar year of the CEO&#x2019;s date of termination or either of the two (2) calendar years immediately preceding the CEO&#x2019;s date of termination. In addition, the CEO shall receive a cash lump sum equal to thirty-six (36) times the reasonably estimated monthly cost of the medical, dental and vision insurance coverage maintained by the Bank for CEO immediately prior to the CEO&#x2019;s date of termination.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the case of the other NEOs, termination of employment by the Corporation without cause or by the NEO with Good Reason after the effective time of a change in control, as defined, results in the same severance payment that would be made in the absence of a change in control.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event of a change in control, and pursuant to the terms of the award agreements between the NEOs and the Corporation, all outstanding and unvested equity awards shall immediately vest. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Good Reason exists if, without the NEO&#x2019;s express written consent, any of the following occurs: (i) the failure to appoint the NEO during the term of the NEOs employment agreement to the executive position occupied by the NEO at the date of commencement of the employment agreement; (ii) a reduction in the NEO&#x2019;s base salary; (iii) the failure of the Bank to maintain the NEO&#x2019;s participation under the Bank&#x2019;s employee benefit, retirement, or material fringe benefit plans, policies, practices, or arrangements in which the NEO participates; or (iv) a relocation of the NEO&#x2019;s principal place of employment by more than 50 miles from the NEO&#x2019;s principal place of employment at the date of commencement of the NEO&#x2019;s employment agreement.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Notwithstanding the foregoing, the change in control severance payments under the employment agreements for the NEOs will be reduced to avoid an excess parachute payment under Section 280G of the Internal Revenue Code if doing so results in a greater after-tax benefit to the NEO.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Each NEO&#x2019;s employment agreement subjects the NEO to non-compete and non-solicitation provisions for a period of two years for the CEO or one year for the other NEOs following their date of termination, provided, however, that such restrictions would not apply in the event of the NEOs termination for cause or termination of employment following a change in control.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The following table sets forth potential payments to the NEOs upon termination of their employment by the Corporation without cause or by the NEOs for Good Reason absent a change in control.&nbsp;&nbsp;The table also sets forth for the NEOs the accelerated vesting, if any, of unvested option and stock awards. </font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:left;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">

		<p style="margin:0pt;background-color: #FFFFFF;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="TransactionsWithManagementAndOthers"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">TRANSACTIONS WITH MANAGEMENT AND OTHERS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Corporation&#x2019;s Corporate Governance Guidelines require the Board to conduct an appropriate review of all related party transactions for potential conflict of interest situations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Related party transactions are those required to be disclosed pursuant to Item 404 of Regulation S-K.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board fulfills the requirement to review related party transactions in conjunction with the Audit Committee, which is comprised entirely of independent directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Governance and Nominating Committee is charged with the responsibility of reviewing and assessing the adequacy of and compliance with the Corporation&#x2019;s Corporate Governance Guidelines and recommending any proposed changes to the Board for approval.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In 1992, the Bank, as tenant, entered into a lease with H. T. Hogan Jr., d/b/a Briar Ridge Properties, covering premises in a building located in Locust Valley, New York, used as a branch office.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Bank subsequently modified and extended the lease in 2002 and 2012.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2012 modification and extension, including the current five-year renewal period, expires on October 31, 2022.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to base rent, the Bank is responsible for its proportionate share of the real estate taxes on the building in which the leased premises are located.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the terms of the lease, the Bank was obligated to pay $44,389 for the year ended December 31, 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2009, the Bank, as tenant, entered into a lease with CSH Realty LLC, covering premises in a building located in Cold Spring Harbor, New York used as a branch office.&nbsp;&nbsp;The lease expires on December 31, 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the terms of the lease, the Bank was obligated to pay $33,014 for the year ended December 31, 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;Howard Thomas Hogan, Jr., a director of the Corporation and the Bank, owns or controls companies that own both properties.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation believes that the terms of the leases are comparable to competitive terms that could have been obtained from an unrelated third party.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Bank has had, and expects to have in the future, banking transactions in the ordinary course of its business with directors, executive officers, principal stockholders of the Corporation and their associates.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such transactions, including borrowings and loan commitments, are made in the ordinary course of business on substantially the same terms, including interest rates and collateral, as those prevailing at the time for comparable transactions with others and, in the opinion of management, do not involve more than a normal risk of collectability nor do they present other unfavorable features.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Certain directors are officers, directors, partners or stockholders of companies or partnerships which, or associates of which, may have been customers of the Bank in the ordinary course of business during 2017 and up to the present time.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additional transactions of this type may occur in the future.&nbsp;&nbsp;All such transactions were effected on substantially the same terms as comparable transactions with other persons.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">SECTION&nbsp;16(A) BEN</font><a name="Section16A"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">EFICIAL OWNERSHIP REPORTING COMPLIANCE</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Our executive officers, directors and beneficial owners of greater than 10% of the outstanding shares of Common Stock are required to file reports with the Securities and Exchange Commission disclosing beneficial ownership and changes in beneficial ownership of our Common Stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;Securities and Exchange Commission rules require disclosure if an executive officer, director or 10% beneficial owner does not file these reports on a timely basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on our review of ownership reports required to be filed for the year ended December 31, 2017, all of these filing requirements were satisfied except for one Form 4 filing for Director Howard Thomas Hogan, Jr. relating to an exercise of stock options on December 13, 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Corporation, on behalf of Director Hogan, inadvertently filed this Form 4 one business</font><font style="display: inline;"> day late on December 18, 2017.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">27</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">RATIFICATION OF APPOINTMENT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The consolidated financial statements of the Corporation for the year ended December 31, 2017 were audited by Crowe Horwath LLP (&#x201C;Crowe Horwath&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;The Audit Committee has appointed Crowe Horwath as the Corporation&#x2019;s independent registered public accounting firm to audit the Corporation&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements for the year ending December 31, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;A resolution will be presented at the Annual Meeting of Stockholders to ratify the appointment of Crowe Horwath.&nbsp;&nbsp;The affirmative vote of the holders of a majority of shares represented in person or by proxy and voting on this item will be required for ratification.&nbsp;&nbsp;If there is no designation on an executed proxy as to how the shares represented should be voted, the proxy will be voted for the ratification.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the stockholders do not ratify the appointment of Crowe Horwath, the Audit Committee will reconsider its selection of Crowe Horwath as the Corporation&#x2019;s independent registered public accounting firm.&nbsp;&nbsp;Even if the stockholders ratify the appointment of Crowe Horwath, the Audit Committee in its discretion may direct the appointment of a different independent registered public accounting firm </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">at any time during the year if it determines that such change is in the best interests of the Corporation and its stockholders.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">A representative of Crowe Horwath will be present at the Annual Meeting of Stockholders and will have the opportunity to make a statement and respond to appropriate questions from stockholders.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">The Board of Directors recommends a vote FOR ratification of the appointment of Crowe Horwath as the Corporation&#x2019;s independent registered public accounting firm.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Audit Fees </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Crowe Horwath&#x2019;s fees for audit services for 2017 and 2016 were $270,000 and $245,000, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase in audit fees is mainly due to the Corporation&#x2019;s continued growth and expansion.&nbsp;&nbsp;Audit services include the following: (1) professional services rendered for the audit of the Corporation&#x2019;s annual consolidated financial statements; (2) reviews of the consolidated financial statements included in the Corporation&#x2019;s Quarterly Reports on Form 10-Q; (3) a reading of the Corporation&#x2019;s Annual Report on Form 10-K; and (4) rendering an opinion on the effectiveness of the Corporation&#x2019;s internal control over financial reporting.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Audit Related Fees</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Audit related fees, as described in Item 9(e)(2) of Schedule 14A of the Securities and Exchange Commission&#x2019;s Proxy Rules, are fees billed to the Corporation by its </font><font style="display: inline;">Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm (&#x201C;Independent Auditors&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;"> for assurance and related services that are reasonably related to the performance of the audit or review of the Corporation&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements and are not audit fees as described in the previous paragraph.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2017, Crowe Horwath did not bill the Corporation for any audit related fees.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2016, Crowe Horwath billed the Corporation $78,000 for work done in connection with a prospectus supplement and two registration statements on Form S-3.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Tax Fees </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Crowe Horwath&#x2019;s fees in 2017 and 2016 for preparing the Corporation&#x2019;s tax returns, providing tax advice and performing tax compliance work were $29,500 and $36,440, respectively.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">All Other Fees</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In neither of the last two fiscal years was the Corporation billed by Crowe Horwath for any fees other than those described above under the captions &#x201C;Audit Fees,&#x201D; &#x201C;Audit Related Fees&#x201D; and &#x201C;Tax Fees.&#x201D; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Audit Committee Approval of Audit Related, Tax and Other Fees</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In 2017 and 2016, the Audit Committee specifically approved or pre-approved all fees reported under the sections &#x201C;Audit Related Fees&#x201D; and &#x201C;Tax Fees.&#x201D;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Engagement of Independent Auditors to Perform Audit Services and Non-Audit Services</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On an annual basis, and in accordance with the terms of written engagement letters, the Audit Committee has engaged the Corporation&#x2019;s Independent Auditors to perform audit services as previously defined and to prepare the Corporation&#x2019;s income tax returns. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In addition, from time to time the Audit Committee may engage the Corporation&#x2019;s Independent Auditors to perform non-audit services such as providing tax advice and performing tax compliance work.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Audit Committee has pre-approved specific types of non-audit services provided that the cost of such services does not exceed $50,000 in any calendar year.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Audit Committee will not engage the Independent Auditors to perform any non-audit service or pre-approve any non-audit service that could impair, in fact or appearance, the independence of the Independent Auditors.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, the Audit Committee will not pre-approve any non-audit service if such pre-approval constitutes delegation to management of the Audit Committee&#x2019;s responsibilities under the 1934 Act.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">28</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt">

			<a href="#TableofContents"><font style="display: inline;font-size:8pt;">Table of Contents</font></a>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">AUDIT COMM</font><a name="AuditCommitteeReport"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">ITTEE REPORT</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Under its charter, the Audit Committee is responsible to </font><font style="display: inline;">assist</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">the Board</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">in</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">fulfilling</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">its</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">oversight</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">responsibilities</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">by</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">reviewing and evaluating: 1) the qualifications and independence of the Independent Auditors; 2) the performance</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">of</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">the</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Corporation&#x2019;s</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Independent Auditors and the internal</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">audit function; 3) the integrity of the Corporation&#x2019;s financial statements; and 4) management&#x2019;s responsibilities to assure that there is in place an effective system of internal controls.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">While the Audit Committee has the responsibilities and powers set forth in this Charter, it is not the duty of the Audit Committee to plan or conduct audits or to determine that the Corporation&#x2019;s financial statements and disclosures are complete and accurate and are in accordance with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) and applicable rules and regulations.&nbsp;&nbsp;These are the responsibilities of management and the Independent Auditors.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Specific duties and responsibilities of the Audit Committee include, among other things:</font><font style="display: inline;"> 1) appoint, retain, compensate, evaluate and, where appropriate, replace the </font><font style="display: inline;">Independent Auditors;&nbsp;&nbsp;2) </font><font style="display: inline;">approve all fees and terms of engagement of the Independent Auditors; 3) confirm the independence of the Independent Auditors; 4) review and discuss with management and the Independent Auditors the Corporation&#x2019;s audited consolidated financial statements and internal control over financial reporting; 5) meet with the Corporation&#x2019;s Independent Auditors and review the scope of audit services and the results of their annual audit of the Corporation&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements, including any recommendations the </font><font style="display: inline;">Independent A</font><font style="display: inline;">uditors may have with respect to internal controls or other business matters; 6) approve the internal audit plan and review the scope and results of internal audits; 7) review the results of examinations performed by regulatory authorities; 8) oversee management&#x2019;s responsibility to fulfill the annual internal control reporting requirements of Section 404 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act and the annual audit and management reporting requirements of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation Improvement Act of 1991; 9) review the Bank's performance of its obligations under various laws and regulations, including those affecting consumers; 10) review </font><font style="display: inline;">related party transactions; and 11) oversee management&#x2019;s responsibility to implement internal controls over information technology and information security risks. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;background-color: #FFFFFF;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The evaluation of the Independent Auditors includes, among other things, a review of the most recent Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (&#x201C;PCAOB&#x201D;) report and </font><font style="display: inline;">communications required by PCAOB Auditing Standard Number 1301 regarding the independence and appointment of the Independent Auditors and the results of the annual audit.&nbsp;&nbsp;The evaluation also includes consideration of the Independent Auditors qualifications and industry experience, the performance of the audit partner and audit team and the tenure and appropriateness of fees.&nbsp;&nbsp;Crowe Horwath has served as the </font><font style="display: inline;">Corporation&#x2019;s I</font><font style="display: inline;">ndependent </font><font style="display: inline;">A</font><font style="display: inline;">uditor</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> since 2003 and the audit partner is rotated at least every five years.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">The Audit Committee received and reviewed the written disclosures and the letter from Crowe Horwath required by applicable requirements of the </font><font style="display: inline;">PCAOB</font><font style="display: inline;"> regarding Crowe Horwath&#x2019;s communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence, and discussed with Crowe Horwath their independence.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Audit Committee reviews and discusses with management and the Independent Auditors the annual audited financial statements, Form 10-K, Forms 10-Q and earnings press releases prior to their filing, including reviewing the disclosures made in "Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operation</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;">."&nbsp;&nbsp;The Audit Committee also reviews and d</font><font style="display: inline;">iscusses policies with respect to risk assessment and risk management.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such discussions include the Corporation&#x2019;s major financial and accounting risk exposures and the steps management has undertaken to control them</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Audit Committee reviews reports from management regarding, among other things, the framework and effectiveness of internal controls over financial reporting and disclosure controls, compliance with laws and regulations, and controls ove</font><font style="display: inline;">r information technology risk.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;background-color: #FFFFFF;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Audit Committee met eight times during 2017 and schedules meetings to ensure it devotes enough time and attention to the duties and responsibilities outlined in this report.&nbsp;&nbsp;Periodic executive sessions are held with the Independent Auditors, Chief Auditor and other members of management to discuss any matters that the Committee or these persons believe should be discussed.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Audit Committee regularly reports its activities to the Board, and annually conducts a review of its Charter and performs a self-assessment.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Based on the review and discussions referred to above, we recommended to the Board that the audited financial statements be included in the Corporation&#x2019;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2017 for filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;text-indent:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Audit Committee:</font>
		</p>
		<div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%; table-layout: fixed;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt;">
			<p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;">
				<font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;font-size:11pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;;"> &#xB7;</font>
			</p>
		</td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top">
			<p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Alexander L. Cover, Chairman</font></p></td></tr></table></div>

			</p>
		</td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top">
			<p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;line-height:100%;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;">
			<font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">John J. Desmond</font></p></td></tr></table></div>
